.PD
{\f[I]clustername\f[]}
.PP
This commands is only run once initially on the first node of the
cluster. It will initialize the cluster configuration, setup the
ssh-keys, start the daemons on the master node, etc. in order to
have a working one-node cluster.
.PP
Note that the \f[I]clustername\f[] is not any random name. It has
to be resolvable to an IP address using DNS, and it is best if you
give the fully-qualified domain name. This hostname must resolve to
an IP address reserved exclusively for this purpose, i.e. not
already in use.
.PP
The cluster can run in two modes: single-home or dual-homed. In the
first case, all traffic (both public traffic, inter-node traffic
and data replication traffic) goes over the same interface. In the
dual-homed case, the data replication traffic goes over the second
network. The \f[B]-s\ (--secondary-ip)\f[] option here marks the
cluster as dual-homed and its parameter represents this node\[aq]s
address on the second network. If you initialise the cluster with
\f[B]-s\f[], all nodes added must have a secondary IP as well.
.PP
Note that for Ganeti it doesn\[aq]t matter if the secondary network
is actually a separate physical network, or is done using
tunneling, etc. For performance reasons, it\[aq]s recommended to
use a separate network, of course.
.PP
The \f[B]--vg-name\f[] option will let you specify a volume group
different than "xenvg" for Ganeti to use when creating instance
disks. This volume group must have the same name on all nodes. Once
the cluster is initialized this can be altered by using the
\f[B]modify\f[] command. If you don\[aq]t want to use lvm storage
at all use the \f[B]--no-lvm-storage\f[] option. Once the cluster
is initialized you can change this setup with the \f[B]modify\f[]
command.
.PP
The \f[B]--master-netdev\f[] option is useful for specifying a
different interface on which the master will activate its IP
address. It\[aq]s important that all nodes have this interface
because you\[aq]ll need it for a master failover.
.PP
The \f[B]--master-netmask\f[] option allows to specify a netmask
for the master IP. The netmask must be specified as an integer, and
will be interpreted as a CIDR netmask. The default value is 32 for
an IPv4 address and 128 for an IPv6 address.
.PP
The \f[B]--use-external-mip-script\f[] option allows to specify
whether to use an user-supplied master IP address setup script,
whose location is
\f[B]@SYSCONFDIR@/ganeti/scripts/master-ip-setup\f[].
If the option value is set to False, the default script (located at
\f[B]@PKGLIBDIR@/tools/master-ip-setup\f[]) will be executed.
.PP
The \f[B]-m\ (--mac-prefix)\f[] option will let you specify a three
byte prefix under which the virtual MAC addresses of your instances
will be generated. The prefix must be specified in the format
\f[B]XX:XX:XX\f[] and the default is \f[B]aa:00:00\f[].
.PP
The \f[B]--no-lvm-storage\f[] option allows you to initialize the
cluster without lvm support. This means that only instances using
files as storage backend will be possible to create. Once the
cluster is initialized you can change this setup with the
\f[B]modify\f[] command.
.PP
The \f[B]--no-etc-hosts\f[] option allows you to initialize the
cluster without modifying the /etc/hosts file.
.PP
The \f[B]--no-ssh-init\f[] option allows you to initialize the
cluster without creating or distributing SSH key pairs.
.PP
The \f[B]--file-storage-dir\f[] option allows you set the directory
to use for storing the instance disk files when using file storage
as backend for instance disks.
.PP
The \f[B]--prealloc-wipe-disks\f[] sets a cluster wide
configuration value for wiping disks prior to allocation. This
increases security on instance level as the instance can\[aq]t
access untouched data from it\[aq]s underlying storage.
.PP
The \f[B]--enabled-hypervisors\f[] option allows you to set the
list of hypervisors that will be enabled for this cluster. Instance
hypervisors can only be chosen from the list of enabled
hypervisors, and the first entry of this list will be used by
default. Currently, the following hypervisors are available:
.TP
.B xen-pvm
Xen PVM hypervisor
.RS
.RE
.TP
.B xen-hvm
Xen HVM hypervisor
.RS
.RE
.TP
.B kvm
Linux KVM hypervisor
.RS
.RE
.TP
.B chroot
a simple chroot manager that starts chroot based on a script at the
root of the filesystem holding the chroot
.RS
.RE
.TP
.B fake
fake hypervisor for development/testing
.RS
.RE
.PP
Either a single hypervisor name or a comma-separated list of
hypervisor names can be specified. If this option is not specified,
only the xen-pvm hypervisor is enabled by default.
.PP
The \f[B]-H\ (--hypervisor-parameters)\f[] option allows you to set
default hypervisor specific parameters for the cluster. The format
of this option is the name of the hypervisor, followed by a colon
and a comma-separated list of key=value pairs. The keys available
for each hypervisors are detailed in the gnt-instance(8) man page,
in the \f[B]add\f[] command plus the following parameters which are
only configurable globally (at cluster level):
.TP
.B migration_port
Valid for the Xen PVM and KVM hypervisors.
.RS
.PP
This options specifies the TCP port to use for live-migration. For
Xen, the same port should be configured on all nodes in the
\f[B]/etc/xen/xend-config.sxp\f[] file, under the key
"xend-relocation-port".
.RE
.TP
.B migration_bandwidth
Valid for the KVM hypervisor.
.RS
.PP
This option specifies the maximum bandwidth that KVM will use for
instance live migrations. The value is in MiB/s.
.PP
This option is only effective with kvm versions >= 78 and qemu-kvm
versions >= 0.10.0.
.RE
.PP
The \f[B]-B\ (--backend-parameters)\f[] option allows you to set
the default backend parameters for the cluster. The parameter
format is a comma-separated list of key=value pairs with the
following supported keys:
.TP
.B vcpus
Number of VCPUs to set for an instance by default, must be an
integer, will be set to 1 if no specified.
.RS
.RE
.TP
.B maxmem
Maximum amount of memory to allocate for an instance by default,
can be either an integer or an integer followed by a unit (M for
mebibytes and G for gibibytes are supported), will be set to 128M
if not specified.
.RS
.RE
.TP
.B minmem
Minimum amount of memory to allocate for an instance by default,
can be either an integer or an integer followed by a unit (M for
mebibytes and G for gibibytes are supported), will be set to 128M
if not specified.
.RS
.RE
.TP
.B auto_balance
Value of the auto_balance flag for instances to use by default,
will be set to true if not specified.
.RS
.RE
.TP
.B always_failover
Default value for the \f[B]always\\_failover\f[] flag for
instances; if not set, \f[B]False\f[] is used.
.RS
.RE
.PP
The \f[B]-N\ (--nic-parameters)\f[] option allows you to set the
default nic parameters for the cluster. The parameter format is a
comma-separated list of key=value pairs with the following
supported keys:
.TP
.B mode
The default nic mode, \[aq]routed\[aq] or \[aq]bridged\[aq].
.RS
.RE
.TP
.B link
In bridged mode the default NIC bridge. In routed mode it
represents an hypervisor-vif-script dependent value to allow
different instance groups. For example under the KVM default
network script it is interpreted as a routing table number or name.
.RS
.RE
.PP
The \f[B]-D\ (--disk-parameters)\f[] option allows you to set the
default disk template parameters at cluster level. The format used
for this option is similar to the one use by the \f[B]-H\f[]
option: the disk template name must be specified first, followed by
a colon and by a comma-separated list of key-value pairs. These
parameters can only be specified at cluster and node group level;
the cluster-level parameter are inherited by the node group at the
moment of its creation, and can be further modified at node group
level using the \f[B]gnt-group\f[](8) command.
.PP
The following is the list of disk parameters available for the
\f[B]drbd\f[] template, with measurement units specified in square
brackets at the end of the description (when applicable):
.TP
.B resync-rate
Static re-synchronization rate. [KiB/s]
.RS
.RE
.TP
.B data-stripes
Number of stripes to use for data LVs.
.RS
.RE
.TP
.B meta-stripes
Number of stripes to use for meta LVs.
.RS
.RE
.TP
.B disk-barriers
What kind of barriers to \f[B]disable\f[] for disks. It can either
assume the value "n", meaning no barrier disabled, or a non-empty
string containing a subset of the characters "bfd". "b" means
disable disk barriers, "f" means disable disk flushes, "d" disables
disk drains.
.RS
.RE
.TP
.B meta-barriers
Boolean value indicating whether the meta barriers should be
disabled (True) or not (False).
.RS
.RE
.TP
.B metavg
String containing the name of the default LVM volume group for DRBD
metadata. By default, it is set to \f[B]xenvg\f[].
It can be overridden during the instance creation process by using
the \f[B]metavg\f[] key of the \f[B]--disk\f[] parameter.
.RS
.RE
.TP
.B disk-custom
String containing additional parameters to be appended to the
arguments list of \f[B]drbdsetup\ disk\f[].
.RS
.RE
.TP
.B net-custom
String containing additional parameters to be appended to the
arguments list of \f[B]drbdsetup\ net\f[].
.RS
.RE
.TP
.B dynamic-resync
Boolean indicating whether to use the dynamic resync speed
controller or not. If enabled, c-plan-ahead must be non-zero and
all the c-* parameters will be used by DRBD. Otherwise, the value
of resync-rate will be used as a static resync speed.
.RS
.RE
.TP
.B c-plan-ahead
Agility factor of the dynamic resync speed controller. (the higher,
the slower the algorithm will adapt the resync speed). A value of 0
(that is the default) disables the controller. [ds]
.RS
.RE
.TP
.B c-fill-target
Maximum amount of in-flight resync data for the dynamic resync
speed controller. [sectors]
.RS
.RE
.TP
.B c-delay-target
Maximum estimated peer response latency for the dynamic resync
speed controller. [ds]
.RS
.RE
.TP
.B c-min-rate
Minimum resync speed for the dynamic resync speed controller.
[KiB/s]
.RS
.RE
.TP
.B c-max-rate
Upper bound on resync speed for the dynamic resync speed
controller. [KiB/s]
.RS
.RE
.PP
List of parameters available for the \f[B]plain\f[] template:
.TP
.B stripes
Number of stripes to use for new LVs.
.RS
.RE
.PP
List of parameters available for the \f[B]rbd\f[] template:
.TP
.B pool
The RADOS cluster pool, inside which all rbd volumes will reside.
When a new RADOS cluster is deployed, the default pool to put rbd
volumes (Images in RADOS terminology) is \[aq]rbd\[aq].
.RS
.RE
.PP
The option \f[B]--maintain-node-health\f[] allows one to
enable/disable automatic maintenance actions on nodes. Currently
these include automatic shutdown of instances and deactivation of
DRBD devices on offline nodes; in the future it might be extended
to automatic removal of unknown LVM volumes, etc. Note that this
option is only useful if the use of \f[B]ganeti-confd\f[] was
enabled at compilation.
.PP
The \f[B]--uid-pool\f[] option initializes the user-id pool. The
\f[I]user-id pool definition\f[] can contain a list of user-ids
and/or a list of user-id ranges. The parameter format is a
comma-separated list of numeric user-ids or user-id ranges. The
ranges are defined by a lower and higher boundary, separated by a
dash. The boundaries are inclusive. If the \f[B]--uid-pool\f[]
option is not supplied, the user-id pool is initialized to an empty
list. An empty list means that the user-id pool feature is
disabled.
.PP
The \f[B]-I\ (--default-iallocator)\f[] option specifies the
default instance allocator. The instance allocator will be used for
operations like instance creation, instance and node migration,
etc. when no manual override is specified. If this option is not
specified and htools was not enabled at build time, the default
instance allocator will be blank, which means that relevant
operations will require the administrator to manually specify
either an instance allocator, or a set of nodes. If the option is
not specified but htools was enabled, the default iallocator will
be \f[B]hail\f[](1) (assuming it can be found on disk). The default
iallocator can be changed later using the \f[B]modify\f[] command.
.PP
The \f[B]--primary-ip-version\f[] option specifies the IP version
used for the primary address. Possible values are 4 and 6 for IPv4
and IPv6, respectively. This option is used when resolving node
names and the cluster name.
.PP
The \f[B]--node-parameters\f[] option allows you to set default
node parameters for the cluster. Please see \f[B]ganeti\f[](7) for
more information about supported key=value pairs.
.PP
The \f[B]-C\ (--candidate-pool-size)\f[] option specifies the
\f[B]candidate_pool_size\f[] cluster parameter. This is the number
of nodes that the master will try to keep as master_candidates. For
more details about this role and other node roles, see the
ganeti(7).
.PP
The \f[B]--specs-...\f[] and \f[B]--ipolicy-disk-templates\f[]
options specify instance policy on the cluster. For the
\f[B]--specs-...\f[] options, each option can have three values:
\f[B]min\f[], \f[B]max\f[] and \f[B]std\f[], which can also be
modified on group level (except for \f[B]std\f[], which is defined
once for the entire cluster). Please note, that \f[B]std\f[] values
are not the same as defaults set by \f[B]--beparams\f[], but they
are used for the capacity calculations. The
\f[B]--ipolicy-disk-templates\f[] option takes a comma-separated
list of disk templates.
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[B]--specs-cpu-count\f[] limits the number of VCPUs that can be
used by an instance.
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[B]--specs-disk-count\f[] limits the number of disks
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[B]--specs-disk-size\f[] limits the disk size for every disk used
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[B]--specs-mem-size\f[] limits the amount of memory available
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[B]--specs-nic-count\f[] sets limits on the number of NICs used
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[B]--ipolicy-disk-templates\f[] limits the allowed disk templates
.PP
For details about how to use \f[B]--hypervisor-state\f[] and
\f[B]--disk-state\f[] have a look at \f[B]ganeti\f[](7).
.SS LIST-TAGS
.PP
\f[B]list-tags\f[]
.PP
List the tags of the cluster.
.SS MASTER-FAILOVER
.PP
\f[B]master-failover\f[] [--no-voting] [--yes-do-it]
.PP
Failover the master role to the current node.
.PP
The \f[B]--no-voting\f[] option skips the remote node agreement
checks. This is dangerous, but necessary in some cases (for example
failing over the master role in a 2 node cluster with the original
master down). If the original master then comes up, it won\[aq]t be
able to start its master daemon because it won\[aq]t have enough
votes, but so won\[aq]t the new master, if the master daemon ever
needs a restart. You can pass \f[B]--no-voting\f[] to
\f[B]ganeti-masterd\f[] on the new master to solve this problem,
and run \f[B]gnt-cluster redist-conf\f[] to make sure the cluster
is consistent again.
.PP
The option \f[B]--yes-do-it\f[] is used together with
\f[B]--no-voting\f[], for skipping the interactive checks. This is
even more dangerous, and should only be used in conjunction with
other means (e.g. a HA suite) to confirm that the operation is
indeed safe.
.SS MASTER-PING
.PP
\f[B]master-ping\f[]
.PP
Checks if the master daemon is alive.
.PP
If the master daemon is alive and can respond to a basic query (the
equivalent of \f[B]gnt-cluster info\f[]), then the exit code of the
command will be 0. If the master daemon is not alive (either due to
a crash or because this is not the master node), the exit code will
be 1.
