.PP
Modify the options for the cluster.
.PP
The \f[B]--vg-name\f[], \f[B]--no-lvm-storage\f[],
\f[B]--enabled-hypervisors\f[],
\f[B]-H\ (--hypervisor-parameters)\f[],
\f[B]-B\ (--backend-parameters)\f[],
\f[B]-D\ (--disk-parameters)\f[], \f[B]--nic-parameters\f[],
\f[B]-C\ (--candidate-pool-size)\f[],
\f[B]--maintain-node-health\f[], \f[B]--prealloc-wipe-disks\f[],
\f[B]--uid-pool\f[], \f[B]--node-parameters\f[],
\f[B]--master-netdev\f[], \f[B]--master-netmask\f[] and
\f[B]--use-external-mip-script\f[] options are described in the
\f[B]init\f[] command.
.PP
The \f[B]--hypervisor-state\f[] and \f[B]--disk-state\f[] options
are described in detail in \f[B]ganeti(7)\f[].
.PP
The \f[B]--add-uids\f[] and \f[B]--remove-uids\f[] options can be
used to modify the user-id pool by adding/removing a list of
user-ids or user-id ranges.
.PP
The option \f[B]--reserved-lvs\f[] specifies a list
(comma-separated) of logical volume group names (regular
expressions) that will be ignored by the cluster verify operation.
This is useful if the volume group used for Ganeti is shared with
the system for other uses. Note that it\[aq]s not recommended to
create and mark as ignored logical volume names which match
Ganeti\[aq]s own name format (starting with UUID and then .diskN),
as this option only skips the verification, but not the actual use
of the names given.
.PP
To remove all reserved logical volumes, pass in an empty argument
to the option, as in \f[B]--reserved-lvs=\f[] or
\f[B]--reserved-lvs\ \[aq]\[aq]\f[].
.PP
The \f[B]-I\ (--default-iallocator)\f[] is described in the
\f[B]init\f[] command. To clear the default iallocator, just pass
an empty string (\[aq]\[aq]).
.PP
The \f[B]--specs-...\f[] and \f[B]--ipolicy-disk-templates\f[]
options are described in the \f[B]init\f[] command.
.PP
See \f[B]ganeti(7)\f[] for a description of \f[B]--submit\f[] and
other common options.
.SS QUEUE
.PP
\f[B]queue\f[] {drain | undrain | info}
.PP
Change job queue properties.
.PP
The \f[B]drain\f[] option sets the drain flag on the job queue. No
new jobs will be accepted, but jobs already in the queue will be
processed.
.PP
The \f[B]undrain\f[] will unset the drain flag on the job queue.
New jobs will be accepted.
.PP
The \f[B]info\f[] option shows the properties of the job queue.
.SS WATCHER
.PP
\f[B]watcher\f[] {pause \f[I]duration\f[] | continue | info}
.PP
Make the watcher pause or let it continue.
.PP
The \f[B]pause\f[] option causes the watcher to pause for
\f[I]duration\f[] seconds.
.PP
The \f[B]continue\f[] option will let the watcher continue.
.PP
The \f[B]info\f[] option shows whether the watcher is currently
paused.
.SS REDIST-CONF
.PP
\f[B]redist-conf\f[] [--submit]
.PP
This command forces a full push of configuration files from the
master node to the other nodes in the cluster. This is normally not
needed, but can be run if the \f[B]verify\f[] complains about
configuration mismatches.
.PP
See \f[B]ganeti(7)\f[] for a description of \f[B]--submit\f[] and
other common options.
.SS REMOVE-TAGS
.PP
\f[B]remove-tags\f[] [--from \f[I]file\f[]] {\f[I]tag\f[]...}
.PP
Remove tags from the cluster. If any of the tags are not existing
on the cluster, the entire operation will abort.
.PP
If the \f[B]--from\f[] option is given, the list of tags to be
removed will be extended with the contents of that file (each line
becomes a tag). In this case, there is not need to pass tags on the
command line (if you do, tags from both sources will be removed). A
file name of - will be interpreted as stdin.
.SS RENAME
.PP
\f[B]rename\f[] [-f] {\f[I]name\f[]}
.PP
Renames the cluster and in the process updates the master IP
address to the one the new name resolves to. At least one of either
the name or the IP address must be different, otherwise the
operation will be aborted.
.PP
Note that since this command can be dangerous (especially when run
over SSH), the command will require confirmation unless run with
the \f[B]-f\f[] option.
.SS RENEW-CRYPTO
.PP
\f[B]renew-crypto\f[] [-f]
.PD 0
.P
.PD
[--new-cluster-certificate]
[--new-confd-hmac-key]
.PD 0
.P
.PD
[--new-rapi-certificate]
[--rapi-certificate
\f[I]rapi-cert\f[]]
.PD 0
.P
.PD
[--new-spice-certificate |
--spice-certificate
\f[I]spice-cert\f[]
.PD 0
.P
.PD
--spice-ca-certificate
\f[I]spice-ca-cert\f[]]
.PD 0
.P
.PD
[--new-cluster-domain-secret]
[--cluster-domain-secret \f[I]filename\f[]]
.PP
This command will stop all Ganeti daemons in the cluster and start
them again once the new certificates and keys are replicated. The
options \f[B]--new-cluster-certificate\f[] and
\f[B]--new-confd-hmac-key\f[] can be used to regenerate the
cluster-internal SSL certificate respective the HMAC key used by
ganeti-confd(8).
.PP
To generate a new self-signed RAPI certificate (used by
ganeti-rapi(8)) specify \f[B]--new-rapi-certificate\f[].
If you want to use your own certificate, e.g. one signed by a
certificate authority (CA), pass its filename to
\f[B]--rapi-certificate\f[].
.PP
To generate a new self-signed SPICE certificate, used by SPICE
connections to the KVM hypervisor, specify the
\f[B]--new-spice-certificate\f[] option. If you want to provide a
certificate, pass its filename to \f[B]--spice-certificate\f[] and
pass the signing CA certificate to \f[B]--spice-ca-certificate\f[].
.PP
\f[B]--new-cluster-domain-secret\f[] generates a new, random
cluster domain secret. \f[B]--cluster-domain-secret\f[] reads the
secret from a file. The cluster domain secret is used to sign
information exchanged between separate clusters via a third party.
.SS REPAIR-DISK-SIZES
.PP
\f[B]repair-disk-sizes\f[] [instance...]
.PP
This command checks that the recorded size of the given
instance\[aq]s disks matches the actual size and updates any
mismatches found. This is needed if the Ganeti configuration is no
longer consistent with reality, as it will impact some disk
operations. If no arguments are given, all instances will be
checked.
.PP
Note that only active disks can be checked by this command; in case
a disk cannot be activated it\[aq]s advised to use
\f[B]gnt-instance activate-disks --ignore-size ...\f[] to force
activation without regard to the current size.
.PP
When the all disk sizes are consistent, the command will return no
output. Otherwise it will log details about the inconsistencies in
the configuration.
.SS SEARCH-TAGS
.PP
\f[B]search-tags\f[] {\f[I]pattern\f[]}
.PP
Searches the tags on all objects in the cluster (the cluster
itself, the nodes and the instances) for a given pattern. The
pattern is interpreted as a regular expression and a search will be
done on it (i.e. the given pattern is not anchored to the beggining
of the string; if you want that, prefix the pattern with ^).
.PP
If no tags are matching the pattern, the exit code of the command
will be one. If there is at least one match, the exit code will be
zero. Each match is listed on one line, the object and the tag
separated by a space. The cluster will be listed as /cluster, a
node will be listed as /nodes/\f[I]name\f[], and an instance as
/instances/\f[I]name\f[].
Example:
.PP
\f[CR]
      #\ gnt-cluster\ search-tags\ time
      /cluster\ ctime:2007-09-01
      /nodes/node1.example.com\ mtime:2007-10-04
\f[]
.SS VERIFY
.PP
\f[B]verify\f[] [--no-nplus1-mem] [--node-group
\f[I]nodegroup\f[]]
.PD 0
.P
.PD
[--error-codes]
[{-I|--ignore-errors}
\f[I]errorcode\f[]]
.PD 0
.P
.PD
[{-I|--ignore-errors}
\f[I]errorcode\f[]...]
.PP
Verify correctness of cluster configuration. This is safe with
respect to running instances, and incurs no downtime of the
instances.
.PP
If the \f[B]--no-nplus1-mem\f[] option is given, Ganeti won\[aq]t
check whether if it loses a node it can restart all the instances
on their secondaries (and report an error otherwise).
.PP
With \f[B]--node-group\f[], restrict the verification to those
nodes and instances that live in the named group. This will not
verify global settings, but will allow to perform verification of a
group while other operations are ongoing in other groups.
.PP
The \f[B]--error-codes\f[] option outputs each error in the
following parseable format:
\f[I]ftype\f[]:\f[I]ecode\f[]:\f[I]edomain\f[]:\f[I]name\f[]:\f[I]msg\f[].
These fields have the following meaning:
.TP
.B ftype
Failure type. Can be \f[I]WARNING\f[] or \f[I]ERROR\f[].
.RS
.RE
.TP
.B ecode
Error code of the failure. See below for a list of error codes.
.RS
.RE
.TP
.B edomain
Can be \f[I]cluster\f[], \f[I]node\f[] or \f[I]instance\f[].
.RS
.RE
.TP
.B name
Contains the name of the item that is affected from the failure.
.RS
.RE
.TP
.B msg
Contains a descriptive error message about the error
.RS
.RE
.PP
\f[B]gnt-cluster\ verify\f[] will have a non-zero exit code if at
least one of the failures that are found are of type
\f[I]ERROR\f[].
.PP
The \f[B]--ignore-errors\f[] option can be used to change this
behaviour, because it demotes the error represented by the error
code received as a parameter to a warning. The option must be
repeated for each error that should be ignored (e.g.:
\f[B]-I\ ENODEVERSION\ -I\ ENODEORPHANLV\f[]). The
\f[B]--error-codes\f[] option can be used to determine the error
code of a given error.
.PP
List of error codes:
.TP
.B \f[B]EINSTANCEWRONGNODE\f[]
Instance running on the wrong node
.RS
.RE
.TP
.B \f[B]ENODEOOBPATH\f[]
Invalid Out Of Band path
.RS
.RE
.TP
.B \f[B]ENODEORPHANINSTANCE\f[]
